The colors in a soap bubble result from the phenomenon of interference. 

When light strikes a soap bubble, some of the light is reflected off the outer surface of the bubble, while some light enters the bubble. This incoming light is partially reflected at the inner surface of the bubble and partially refracted into the bubble. These two beams of light interact with each other, leading to interference patterns. Depending on the thickness of the soap film, these light waves either reinforce each other (constructive interference), creating regions of intense color, or cancel each other out (destructive interference), resulting in regions of no color or different colors.

Thus, the correct choice is:

E: interference
